19:
So you want to be one of our
satellite states?
20:
If I remember correctly, your tune
used to be you'd sooner sink to the
bottom of the ocean then sink so
low as to join Gaea. Why the change
of heart?
25:
We used to get big hurly-burlies like
this once a year at most. In the past
few months, we've had dozens. And
the next onslaught keeps comin'
sooner and sooner.
28:
Honestly speaking, I would've
preferred keeping you independent.
It's a crying shame.
30:
We're sorry, Selene, but will ya help
us?
32:
Of course. I've got a reputation to
uphold.
39:
The monsters are streaming in from
the north. There must be some kind
of reason. Environmental
degradation, a disruption in the
food chain...
47:
The Sage of the Sea... Thank you for
taking the pains to come. Do you
have any information?
53:
Legend tells of a beast that
appeared when this world sank to
the bottom of the sea. It is also
called the Leviathan.
54:
It's said to be sleeping north of our
sacred lands, in a place of water
and shadows, where even merfolk
dare not venture.
56:
The northern waters, huh? The
teeming of monsters there is so
thick even the Navy can't cut
through it. Seems like this Maw of
yours is more than a cute children's
story.
58:
Something has risen from the
depths...
60:
And now it's cutting south, leaving a
trail of filth in its wake as black as
pitch itself.
61:
The sea creatures that have
encroached on your territory are not
part of a bold invasion, but rather... a
panicked retreat.
63:
And the true invader? Where is it
now?
66:
And now, human, you find yourself
face-to-face with the same
question that has haunted every
beast of land or sea since the
beginning of time. Fight or flight?
70:
So what you're saying is, they won't
send reinforcements.
72:
No, it's fine. I saw this coming. The
admiral has less spine than a
jellyfish. Not to mention I don't have
the time to confront him myself.
82:
Good little kids should be in bed by
now.
86: Would you mind not calling me a kid?
90:
I call it as I see it. Admit it. You hate
the label because you know it's true.
95:
Don't change the subject. Is or isn't
your no-good Navy gonna let this
place sink?
98:
Let me make one thing clear. Up top,
they're not cold-blooded. They just
lack initiative.
101:
"Are all the reports true? What risks
are involved? Should we investigate
the matter further?"
102:
These questions have never once
crossed their drowsy old brains.
They keep them out because they're
scared of them, like how you'd shut
a ghoul out of your house.
104:
After all, the more they know, the
more responsible they can be held
for their inaction.
109:
Then this country is ruled by
cowards.
113:
Not everyone can be brave, chubby
cheeks. I think it's rather cruel, not
allowing people their little
weaknesses.
114:
And anyways... You don't know them
like I do.
123:
Big boy, isn't he? I can see him from
all the way over here.
124: We'd better get him a fitting toy.
129:
Guess he liked it.
Well?! Don't hold back!
131:
All ships, open fire! I want every last
cannonball buried in its scales!
140:
Look at the size of that fleet. I
thought they weren't sending you
backup!
144:
Many are not Navy vessels... I see
the flags of corsairs!
149:
Everyone, meet my lackies. I told
them this was their chance to be in
a sea battle to end all sea battles,
and they came flocking over.
Impressionable ducklings, aren't
they?
157: The death cry of the Maw...
161:
Playtime wasn't nearly as exciting as
I'd expected. Maybe... that wasn't the
Maw at all.
162:
Let's not consider the war won just
yet.
163:
Which leads me to our next
problem. I don't have any more
tricks up my sleeve.
165: Unless you're willing to pitch in.
174:
Wonderful. Either way, I think we've
earned the right to a little
celebration. I can also introduce to
you to my adorable ducklings.
176:
Well, come on. It's the start of a long
night for you.
